<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<worksheet>
  <title>Section 1.2 - Reduced row echelon form (Part 2)</title>
  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>Make sure you can answer the following questions:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li><p>When is a matrix in reduced row echelon form?</p></li>
      <li><p>Describe how to put a matrix in reduced row echelon from.</p></li>
      <li><p>How do we use the reduced row echelon form to determine the solution space?</p></li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
      <p>Consider each of the following augmented matrices.  In the class prep you determined if these were in reduced row echelon form.  If a matrix is not in reduced row echelon form, either (a) perform a
  sequence of scaling, interchange, and replacement operations to
  obtain a row equivalent matrix that is in reduced row echelon form or (b) use Sage to find the row reduced echelon form.
  Then use the reduced row echelon matrix to determine whether there
  is a single solution, infinitely many solutions, or no solutions.
  If there are infinitely many, identify free and basic variables.</p>
      <p><m>\ds
  \left[
    \begin{array}{rrr|r}
      2 \amp 0 \amp 4 \amp -8 \\
      0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 2 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
  </m></p>
      <p><m>\ds
  \left[
    \begin{array}{rrr|r}
      1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\
      0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
  </m></p>
      <p><m>\ds
  \left[
    \begin{array}{rrr|r}
      1 \amp 0 \amp 4 \amp 2 \\
      0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 2 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
  </m></p>
      <p><m>
  \left[
    \begin{array}{rrr|r}
      0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 2 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
      1 \amp 0 \amp 4 \amp 2 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
  </m></p>
      <p><m>\ds
  \left[
    \begin{array}{rrr|r}
      1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \amp 2 \\
      0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
  </m></p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>Suppose that the reduced row echelon form of a matrix looks like
  <m>\ds
  \left[
    \begin{array}{rrrr|r}
      1 \amp * \amp 0 \amp * \amp * \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp * \amp * \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
    \end{array}
  \right].
  </m>
  What, if anything, does the last row tell you about the solution
  space?</p>
      <p>Suppose that the reduced row echelon form of a matrix looks like
  <m>\ds
  \left[
    \begin{array}{rrrr|r}
      1 \amp * \amp 0 \amp * \amp * \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp * \amp * \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
    \end{array}
  \right].
  </m>
  What, if anything, does the last row tell you about the solution
  space?</p>
      <p>If a linear system has no solutions, how can you tell by looking at
  the reduced row echelon form of its augmented matrix.</p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>Consider the system of linear equations:</p>
      <p><m>\ds
  \begin{alignedat}{4}
    x \amp  {}+{}  \amp 2y \amp  {}-{}  \amp z \amp  {}={}  \amp 2 \\
    -2x \amp  {}-{}  \amp 2y \amp  {}+{}  \amp 4z \amp  {}={}  \amp -4 \\
    x \amp {}-{} \amp 2y \amp  {}-{}  \amp 6z \amp  {}={}  \amp 3 \\
  \end{alignedat}
  </m></p>
      <p>Form the associated augmented matrix and perform Gaussian
  elimination (or use Sage) to find its reduced row echelon form.  What does this
  tell you about the solution space of the system?</p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

</worksheet>
